  "image_index": [
    {
      "key": "wide-canyon-overview",
      "frame_id": "frame-01",
      "frame_index": 1,
      "description": "Sheet 1, image 1. Opening frame. Wide aerial-style view of eroded terracotta canyon ridges with the green valley below. Subject fills the upper two-thirds; negative space opens along the bottom edge where the valley drops away. Text anchored bottom-left with a to-bottom gradient. A single terracotta divider line separates the headline from the subtitle — typographic punctuation, not decoration. Focal point set to x_pct 45, y_pct 40 to keep the ridge drama and distant valley both in frame. Strongest wide-angle composition in the series; earns the opening position."
    },
    {
      "key": "eroded-channels-closeup",
      "frame_id": "frame-02",
      "frame_index": 2,
      "description": "Sheet 1, image 4. Radical shift from wide to extreme close-up. Dense labyrinthine channel texture fills the entire frame — the image itself is the texture. No shapes added: any decorative element would compete with or poorly imitate what the photograph already shows with far greater complexity. Single stat anchored bottom-right with a soft to-bottom gradient preserving the texture through most of the frame. Focal point centered. The stat gives geological scale to what otherwise reads as pure abstraction."
    },
    {
      "key": "columnar-formations",
      "frame_id": "frame-03",
      "frame_index": 3,
      "description": "Sheet 1, image 5. Towering rust-orange columnar formations under a pale sky. Subject rises from the lower half; negative space sits in the upper sky. Text anchored bottom-left with a to-bottom gradient. No decorative shapes: the formations themselves are the vertical geometry — adding column shapes would be redundant illustration of what the photograph already provides. Orange tag establishes zone identity; temperature stat gives the visitor a visceral data point about this specific area. Focal point at x_pct 50, y_pct 60 to keep the full column height in frame."
    },
    {
      "key": "isolated-mesa",
      "frame_id": "frame-04",
      "frame_index": 4,
      "description": "Sheet 1, image 6. Isolated butte with a small scrubby tree on the summit, warm side light, rich eroded texture. Complete silence — no text, no shapes, no overlay gradient. The image is compositionally self-contained and needs no help. A minimal flat mood overlay at 0.18 opacity maintains series color temperature without darkening the subject. Focal point at x_pct 55, y_pct 50 to keep the mesa centered while preserving the open earth foreground."
    },
    {
      "key": "barrel-cactus-bloom",
      "frame_id": "frame-05",
      "frame_index": 5,
      "description": "Sheet 1, image 2. First sign of life in an otherwise geological series. Barrel cactus with vivid pink bloom, rain-wet spines, rich greens against rust earth. Subject occupies center-left; negative space opens in the darker earth background to the right and below. No shapes added: the cactus and bloom carry all the organic movement the frame needs — an arc shape would try to replicate what the plant already does naturally. Stat gives height context; italic caption marks the tonal shift from geology to biology. Focal point at x_pct 50, y_pct 55 to keep bloom and full cactus body in frame."
    },
    {
      "key": "burrowing-owls",
      "frame_id": "frame-06",
      "frame_index": 6,
      "description": "Sheet 1, image 7. Two burrowing owls in sharp focus, golden backlight, wild grasses in the foreground. Subject sits center-frame; negative space opens in the lower foreground grasses and the soft upper sky. Four grass blade lines at the left and right frame edges — the only frame with decorative shapes. Justified: the tight crop partially obscures the habitat context; the blades place the owls inside the tall dry grass of the Tatacoa, reinforcing environment that the photograph implies but does not fully show. Opacity held between 0.15 and 0.22. Scientific name as hero text; tag and label complete the wildlife identification register."
    },
    {
      "key": "motorcyclist-dirt-road",
      "frame_id": "frame-07",
      "frame_index": 7,
      "description": "Sheet 1, image 8. Closing frame. Lone motorcyclist on a dirt road, telegraph poles, layered mountain ridges fading into haze. The only frame with human presence in motion — gives the series a sense of departure and scale. No decorative shapes: the road and mountain layers in the photograph already provide all spatial depth and perspective. Text anchored bottom-left. Terracotta divider line echoes frame-01, closing the series with the same typographic punctuation used to open it. Focal point at x_pct 50, y_pct 52 to preserve road convergence and mountain silhouettes."
    }
  ]
}
